Author: dzmiguel
Content:
I've been super drained lately, not physically, but mentally. And honestly, it's mostly because of my own parents.
I've been seriously thinking about cutting ties with them. I mean, if they call me a "Anak Durhaka", so be it, right? I haven't even replied to their chats for the past 10 days.

I've been living separately from my parents for a while now. They're in Bogor, and I'm in an apartment in Jakarta. 

My dad's in his 70s, and my mom's in her late 50s. I'm my mom's only child; she's my dad's second wife (he divorced his first wife when he was young). From my dad's side, I'm his third child.

Anyway, my dad's hooked on online gambling. It's so hard to talk sense into him, even his own family can't get through to him.

Three years ago, my paternal grandparents passed away and left a pretty substantial inheritance to their kids. If they'd just lived normally, even a bit extravagantly, it would have been more than enough. But in just three years, my dad blew it all on gambling and now he's in the red. The only asset left is their house, which they're trying to sell because I hear there are debts everywhere ‚Äì I'm not sure of the exact amount. My dad's car (BPKB) is also pawned at the bank for a loan. And it seems like the money from that car loan is gone, and he can't even make the payments anymore. 

Now, they're chasing me to help them pawn my car's (BPKB) at the bank for another loan for my dad. They promise they'll pay it back when the house sells, they buy a smaller one, and pay off all their debts.

I'm not replying because I absolutely do not want my car's BPKB pawned at the bank. The risk of default is super high, and it feels like they're just digging a deeper hole. If they default, my BI Checking (credit score) will be screwed because it's under my name, and I feel like I'll need a good BI Checking for everything in my future.

Author: dzmiguel
Content:
Their house has been listed for sale for about six months now, and honestly, I don't think it'll sell anytime soon. The location isn't great ‚Äì it's in a housing complex but in the back. Plus, the price is pretty high, so it's tough to sell, especially with the current economy.

That's why I think it's bullshit that they'll pay off all their debts once the house sells. It'll take forever, or it might not even sell at all.

And now, on top of the bank stuff, my dad also has debts with a bunch of relatives, like here and there, close and distant family, it seems he owes money to a lot of them, and it's just coming out more and more. So yeah, for sure this thing about borrowing my car's BPKB, there's no way it'll get paid back, it's just to dig himself into an even bigger hole. 

When they first bought that house with his inheritance money, I was against it. It was overpriced and far from everything, but my father insisted. I could only give advice; there was nothing else I could do, it was his money anyway. So I didn't really care.

Now it's just making my life complicated; they keep messaging me.

Author: dzmiguel
Content:
I'm 30 now, and I also feel like I've never been supported as a kid. I've always had to figure things out on my own. Even though I haven't "made it" yet and my work is a bit all over the place, I can survive living on my own in Jakarta. Right now, I work as a ride-share driver, a plane ticket broker, handle driving licenses, ETLE (electronic traffic law enforcement), visas, etc. There are always ways to survive in Jakarta. You can still find cheap food, like 10-15k Rupiah meals at warteg (local eateries), and I'm always looking for promotions. When I used to live with them, they never supported any of my business ideas, saying "why do that, why start that business, you'll just lose money." My dad had it easy back then with my grandparents around to support him, always hoping for that inheritance. Now my grandparents are gone, and the inheritance is gone too, all vanished because of gambling.

I just wanted to share my story here.
For those of you who are thinking about getting married or are looking for a partner, please find someone who is truly good, doesn't gamble, and is responsible.
Because otherwise, your kids will end up carrying the family's burdens and stress.
I feel lucky that this problem came up now that I live alone. I can truly ignore all calls and chats from my parents. If I were still living with them, it would be a total nightmare.
It's exhausting having parents like that, but I'm still trying to stay strong. I really want to blow up the whole situation to the extended family so they know what my parents are really like. But I'm still holding back.

Basically, don't get married if you're not ready mentally either, because your kids will pay the price.

Stay strong, everyone!
Sorry this is so long. I don't know where else to share this. I'm still not brave enough to post it on my personal Facebook or Instagram because there's a lot of family there. Here, I can be half anonymous.
Thanks!

Author: monke_eat_banana
Content:
Yeah, but procrastination is a lot more complicated than I originally thought. Basically it could be categorized into 3 types:
- Idealistic Procrastination
Basically holding off from doing something because I want to "wait for the right moment". Perfectionism falls under this category.
> *"I am supposed to to this assignment, but right now I'm not feeling inspired/motivated so I'll only start doing it after I feel better."*
> 
> *"I really lonely and want to find someone, but I'm not confident in myself so I'll only start looking after I have a (good job)/(better body after going to the gym)/(better appearance after consistent skincare and get better clothing)."*

- Avoidance Procrastination
Procrastination in order to avoid/postpone a negative emotion.
> *"I know I have to finish my college work, but the work is incredibly boring and the last assignment I completed did not even get a good grade so why bother? I'd do anything to avoid boredom."*
> 
> *"I want to open up to my parents on my suicidal thoughts due to me believing that I'm a failure, but I'm scared that they'll see me differently because of it. I'm scared that I'll become a bigger burden to them"*

- Operational Procrastination
Procrastination because the task I'm supposed to be doing is too abstract. Usually happens for tasks that needed to be broken down into practical steps, for example:
> I'm supposed to begin writing my thesis. But I don't even have the slightest idea what needs to be prepared and what the steps are. In the end, I'd procrastinate simply because I don't know what tangible action I could do today.

Being able to notice & identify all the friction my mind makes which caused procrastination is really difficult

Author: cabbagexu
Content: not sure where these categories are from, but my friend and I had another type of procrastination, which can fall under the term "avoidance procrastination", but has a different reasoning

Author: cabbagexu
Content: we procrastinated because of the fear of failure, which sounds counter-intuitive because not procrastinating is the easiest way to avoid failure

Author: cabbagexu
Content: but we were perfectionists and we were afraid of producing something that isn't perfect (let's say a B+ or an A instead of an A+)

Author: cabbagexu
Content: if we didn't procrastinate and didn't get A+, we "failed" because we were incompetent

Author: cabbagexu
Content: if we procrastinated and got an A, we had a reason for our failure: a time constraint

Author: cabbagexu
Content: so if any folks here have that type of procrastination, remember: perfect is the enemy of good

Author: alinn3662
Content:
Sorry guys, I'm chatting in this chat room, but I don't have anyone to talk to rn.
A few minutes ago, I just had a serious conversation with my bf, who said he wanted to marry me a few months ago,  already contacted my parents, and I'd gotten to know his family well. But after learning about my symptoms of BPD, he changed his mind and said something hurtful about my BPD. I'm crying in the bathroom rn, feeling incredibly sad. It's as if he can break the commitment bcs I can't be mentally stable (which takes a long time to recover).
I feel unlovable and unsupported. I feel incredibly insecure and rejected. If people say so easily, "Don't end your life," why hasn't anyone stayed by my side and encouraged me to keep living?

Author: alinn3662
Content: Please tell me, if there's still hope for someone with mental disorder like me üôÇ

Author: latte5774
Content:
Im so sorry to hear that. Not only you lost a future that youre ready to go into, but also being hurt in identity-level kind of way. We‚Äôre glad that you choose to say something about it, anyone in your position would be wrecked üíî

Let me say this clearly, because your brain is being cruel to you right now:
**Having BPD symptoms does not make you unlovable, disposable, or unworthy of commitment.**

It means you‚Äôre human, dealing with something real, and healing takes time. That‚Äôs not a flaw, okay? 

About what he said, this is my personal opinion, so take it with a grain of salt. I think it crossed a line. It‚Äôs one thing to feel scared or unprepared. It‚Äôs another thing to weaponize your mental health and make it sound like you are the problem. That doesn‚Äôt mean you‚Äôre ‚Äútoo much.‚Äù It means he didn‚Äôt have the capacity he thought he did. 

‚ÄúIf people say ‚Äòdon‚Äôt end your life,‚Äô why hasn‚Äôt anyone stayed?‚Äù

Yeah. Sometimes people are loud about wanting us alive but quiet when it comes to showing up. **That‚Äôs a failure on them, not proof that your life isn‚Äôt worth staying for.**

Right now, please focus on one thing only: you are not alone in this moment, even if it feels like it. 

You don‚Äôt need to solve your relationship tonight.
You don‚Äôt need to decide your worth tonight.
You just need to get through this hour.

**P.s. You are worthy of love that doesn‚Äôt disappear when things get hard.** Even if your heart can‚Äôt believe that yet, it‚Äôs still true.

As latte put it, you are feeling things, yes, it is human, dealing with a bad situation, and as shitty as it is, it is natural for you to react this way when you've got something that's bad happening in your life, 

But I'd like to stress once again **You are not your BPD**, **You and BPD are a separate entity and it does not define you**

Author: meyokoe
Content:
Hey, its fine

As someone who lives with BPD, i do understand how you feel, and what shibe and latte says are right, don't blame yourself either, you are you, and I'm sure that the things you did are not caused by you, but your BPD, and even then, now that you know you have it, you know that it isnt you who is willingly wanting to become like this.

I dont know who you are personally, but i'm glad youre still here with us to tell, and, this is gonna sound very counterintuitive and i dont mean this in a bad way, but now that your bf (or ex if thats the case) has shown his true colours, it is clear to you that it could've ended worse if you discover it later on.

I know that everyone here can only help to some point, but youre free to talk here. This is a safe space for everyone and don't be afraid to ask for help even with strangers, okay?

Author: pompompuringdom
Content:
My love, I'm so sorry I missed this last night, and I'm so sorry that this is the way your ex-boyfriend chooses to respond to you and your symptoms, and that now you are left to feel like this. It's so incredibly callous and unfair, and honestly it says a lot about who he is, what his values are, his attitude towards the topic of mental health, and also his conflict resolution skills (which clearly, are shit).

You are always worthy of love and support, don't let one man make you forget that. I know lots of people with BPD (@amiyazo, @cwk | angerypdd...) and they are able to live fruitful, fulfilled and flourishing lives once they do get that love and support from the people around them. Often times, there's nothing all that wrong with you, but there's all things wrong with your environment.

Author: latte5774
Content:
Ok first of all, you wanting and recognizing a rage problem is already 30% cured. Lets look at the other 70%:

in my own experience when i feel like im about to flip out, i ask myself this: ‚Äúwill i care about it in 24 hours?‚Äù If the answer is not, its probably not worth getting your veins popping. And then practice what i called ‚Äúdelayed reaction‚Äù, like, not everything requires you to reply instantly, take a good 10 secs to think about it, and ask yourself ‚Äúdo i care enough for this?‚Äù Almost always works like a charm. 

And then. I recommend to like, sleep well every night, and please reduce caffeine intake <~ this is almost always a culprit.
